<dl id="n14025a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14025a">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14025a"> 25(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> I ch. / i</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">And this true Soul of Germany is nothing less than the living Christ, as is witnessed by the genius of German speech, which uses I.CH. (&ldquo;Jesus Christus&rdquo;) for the first person, instead of the Englishman&apos;s &ldquo;I&rdquo;, or the Frenchman&apos;s &ldquo;je,&rdquo; thereby appealing to every German to reveal the immense depths and sublimities of the human soul. <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) xviii</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
